So, to maintain O2 evolution and linear electron transport under low light, PSII must keep the rate constant for the recombination\
S2QA-  ->  S1QA\
\
much slower than the delivery rate for photons absorbed by PSII; otherwise, a photon absorbed by PSII will be dissipated by recombination before the arrival of the next photon.\
\
The recombination has an activation energy, and proceeds at temperatures above an activation temperature in the range of 5 to 30C.\
\
Hypothesis:\
Cells growing at low temperatures may suppress recombination losses from charge separations, allowing them to exploit photons arriving with wide time spacing.\
\
Test:\
The fluorescence yield of an individual PSII oscillates in a 4 step cycle,  depending upon the S-state of the OEC.\
A pool of PSII, starting from darkness, will ~all be in S1.\
During a series of STSF, the pooled fluorescence yield will oscillate in a 4 step cycle;  but damping of the oscillation occurs as individual PSII fall out of step with the pool through 'missed' steps when an STSF fails to advance a PSII to the next S state.\
\
Recombination while waiting for the next photon contributes to 'missed' steps.\
\
Damping of oscillation should increase with increasing spacing of STSF\
Growth conditions (or taxa) that suppress recombination should maintain measurable oscillation of PSII fluorescence for more steps, than growth conditions (or taxa) more prone to recombination losses.\
